{"candidates":[{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness criticism strictly beats self-consistency only when SC majority is wrong (base error > 1-1/k) AND critic recall on the dominant-wrong answer is high enough to flip the plurality after filtering; it strictly loses whenever critic precision is low enough that false flags on correct minority candidates erode a formerly correct majority below the post-filter plurality threshold.\", \"mechanism\": \"SC elects the pre-filter modal answer. Harness elects the post-filter modal answer. For harness to strictly beat SC, at least one question where SC was wrong must flip to correct (critic flags enough wrong-majority candidates to drop them below the surviving minority), AND zero questions where SC was right may flip to wrong (critic must not flag so many correct-majority candidates that a surviving wrong minority overtakes them). Define p = per-candidate base error, phi = critic recall on wrong answers, psi = critic precision (fraction of flags that are truly wrong). The strict-win regime requires: (A) p > 1 - 1/k (so the wrong answer holds plurality pre-filter), and (B) phi * count(wrong_majority) > count(wrong_majority) - count(correct_minority) (filtering drops wrong below correct), and (C) (1-psi) * count(correct_majority) < count(correct_majority) - count(wrong_minority) for every question where SC was right (false flags do not let a wrong minority overtake). Condition C is the loss mode: when psi is low, false flags on correct-majority candidates can hand the win to a surviving wrong minority. The repository data sit in the null zone: p <= 1/k so SC majorities are already correct, making condition A unsatisfied and guaranteeing net fixed-minus-broke <= 0.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"base error p in (1-1/k, 1.0)\", \"critic recall phi high enough to flip plurality\", \"critic precision psi high enough to avoid eroding correct majorities\", \"k >= 3\"], \"excludes\": [\"p <= 1-1/k where SC is already correct on vast majority of questions\", \"critic with psi near 0 that flags indiscriminately\", \"k=1 or k=2\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At p=0.55 and k=5, harness accuracy is NOT at least 5 percentage points above SC accuracy, with at least 3 questions flipping from wrong-under-SC to correct-under-harness and 0 questions flipping from right-to-wrong\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At p=0.55, psi=0.15 (low precision), k=5, harness accuracy is NOT below SC accuracy, with at least 2 questions flipping from right-under-SC to wrong-under-harness due to false flags eroding correct majorities\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At p=0.15 and k=5, harness accuracy differs from SC accuracy by more than 2 percentage points in either direction\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This is the canonical mechanism-first partition: strict improvement requires a wrong SC majority to fix, and a precise-enough critic to fix it without breaking correct ones. The loss mode (false flags erode correct majorities) is the natural counterexample to any claim that filtering is monotonically beneficial. The experiment sweeps p (via task difficulty) and psi (via critic prompting) orthogonally to isolate both the win and loss regimes.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"5b4538abe4a712f8c9c0a33fe17fe62d43ac359f1375d97921d389955ef1f08a"},{"role":"dependence","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"},{"role":"mention","target":"62a4b88b39115620483d82db6756e4f3c9d86261fa24593ffa7bb2ca8aba0a16"}],"typicality":0.9},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"No fixed (p, phi, psi, k) regime is sufficient to predict strict harness advantage; the determining factor is question-conditional alignment between the critic's discrimination signal and the specific candidate-level error structure, so strict improvement arises only when the critic's flag rate is higher on wrong-majority candidates than on correct-majority candidates within each question.\", \"mechanism\": \"For each question q, let r_w(q) = fraction of wrong candidates flagged, r_c(q) = fraction of correct candidates flagged. Harness strictly beats SC on q iff SC was wrong AND r_w(q) * n_wrong(q) > n_wrong(q) - n_correct(q) AND for all other questions q' where SC was right, r_c(q') * n_correct(q') < n_correct(q') - n_wrong(q'). The global averages (p, phi, psi) do not determine the per-question sign of (r_w - r_c); the same global averages can produce strict wins or strict losses depending on whether the critic's errors are concentrated on wrong-majority questions (helpful) or correct-majority questions (harmful). The repository's null results are consistent: even with recall=1.0 on the hard set, the flagged candidates were on questions where SC was already right, so no fixable-wrong-majority existed.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"question-conditional critic flag rates\", \"base error p in (0.4, 0.8) where SC is wrong on a nontrivial fraction\", \"k >= 3\", \"critic with flag rate correlated with candidate correctness at the question level\"], \"excludes\": [\"critic with uniform random flag rates independent of candidate correctness\", \"p <= 1/k (no wrong SC majorities to fix)\", \"claims that global precision/recall alone predict strict advantage\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Two conditions with identical global (p=0.5, phi=0.6, psi=0.5, k=5) but different per-question flag-correlation structure produce harness-vs-SC deltas that differ by less than 10 percentage points, falsifying the claim that per-question structure matters more than global averages\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Harness accuracy is NOT strictly above SC accuracy in the high per-question flag-correlation condition, despite SC being wrong on at least 30% of questions\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"In the low per-question flag-correlation condition (flags independent of correctness), harness does NOT lose relative to SC on at least 15% of questions where SC was right\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This candidate attacks the premise that a fixed regime suffices, arguing from the per-question structure. The decisive experiment uses a controlled critic (synthetic flag mask with tunable per-question correlation) to decouple global precision/recall from per-question alignment, directly testing whether the same global averages can yield both strict wins and strict losses.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"},{"role":"dependence","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"},{"role":"dependence","target":"ba687c5f145e404c53a84549cf366e0b6e0106eec67404c07231357fed09e672"}],"typicality":0.65},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"The strict-win regime exists only in a narrow intermediate band of base error (roughly 0.55 to 0.75 at k=5) combined with high critic recall (phi > 0.7) and moderate precision (psi > 0.3); at lower p, SC is already correct (nothing to fix); at higher p, no surviving correct minority remains to benefit from filtering; the strict-loss regime emerges when psi < 0.2 and SC was right, because false flags fragment the correct majority.\", \"mechanism\": \"At k=5 with p=0.55 (3 wrong, 2 correct typically), a critic with phi=0.7 flags ~2 of 3 wrong candidates, dropping the wrong count to ~1 while the 2 correct survive (if psi=0.3, ~0.4 correct are falsely flagged, so ~1.6 survive), and harness elects the correct answer. At p=0.75 (4 wrong, 1 correct), even perfect recall leaves 0-1 wrong candidates but only 1 correct, so filtering cannot create a correct plurality — at best a tie. At p=0.15 with low psi=0.15, the 4-5 correct candidates suffer ~0.6-0.75 false flags, and if even one wrong candidate survives unflagged, a 3-correct-vs-1-wrong majority can become 2-vs-1, still correct; but at k=7, p=0.15, psi=0.15, the 6 correct candidates suffer ~0.9 false flags, and 1 wrong candidate survives, giving 5.1-vs-1, still correct — so the loss mode requires psi low enough that false flags exceed the majority margin. The loss condition is: (1-psi) * n_correct > n_correct - n_wrong, i.e., false flags on correct candidates exceed the SC majority margin.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"p in (0.5, 0.8) at k=5\", \"phi > 0.6\", \"psi in (0.2, 0.5)\", \"k=5\", \"loss regime: p < 1/k, psi < majority_margin / n_correct\"], \"excludes\": [\"p > 0.8 (no surviving correct minority)\", \"p < 0.3 with psi > 0.3 (false flags too few to erode majority)\", \"k=2 (no meaningful plurality dynamics)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At p=0.65, phi=0.75, psi=0.35, k=5, harness accuracy is NOT at least 8 percentage points above SC accuracy\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At p=0.15, psi=0.1, k=5, harness accuracy is NOT at least 3 percentage points below SC accuracy, with at least 2 right-to-wrong flips from false flags\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At p=0.85, k=5, harness accuracy exceeds SC accuracy by more than 2 percentage points despite phi=1.0\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This candidate makes a concrete quantitative band prediction with specific thresholds, making it highly falsifiable. The experiment uses task-difficulty scaling to hit p=0.65 and p=0.85, and critic-prompt aggressiveness to hit psi=0.35 vs psi=0.10. The key risk is that p and psi may not be independently controllable on this provider.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"5b4538abe4a712f8c9c0a33fe17fe62d43ac359f1375d97921d389955ef1f08a"},{"role":"dependence","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"},{"role":"mention","target":"f7c88d08c494a83766a8454ca9a977a013b3694e868b7aab5de870943489d98f"}],"typicality":0.35}]}